Harvard: Students take rest classes
This year, Harvard University has established a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and to fight the growing male tendency to study using caffeine all night long.
One teacher noticed that most of the students at the world's top university can't take care of them.
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the first of the genres in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him
At the end, a student approached me and said, "Why do you tell me that only in the last year?"
She claimed that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
First spent this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their school and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Director General of University Health Services, stated that the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that the students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The course time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, baskets, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how the lack of long-term sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We know that this will not change the behavior of students instantly.
However, in our view, they have the right to know this information - in the same way as you have the right to know what the effects of smoking on health," added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride of "a white night" still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students make lack of sleep an increasing problem.
Having sufficient and good quality sleep should be "the secret weapon" of students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid taking weight, because the lack of sleep puts the brain in an inanition mode, making them hungry permanently.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student in chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said that this course had opened his eyes and moved him to insist that it be offered on the whole campus.
He hoped that the next step would be to propose to all third-cycle students to follow a similar study program before joining the deemed institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students provide an alarm for both sleep and waking hours, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disturb their circadian rhythm and cause sleep disturbances.
