Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, launches a brand new company that seeks to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technological legend project, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of Berners-Lee's free platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and those who are allowed to access such information.
In an exclusive interview given to Fast Company, Berners-Lee said in a joke that Inrupt was meant to "dominate the world".
"We have to do it now," he said about the launch.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid technology to enable people to create their own "on-line personal data store" or DPL.
It may contain contact lists, task lists, a calendar, a music library and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available at the same time on a single browser.
The particularity of the online personal data store is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access what type of information.
The company calls this "personal responsibility through data".
According to company CEO John Bruce, Inrupt's idea is that the company provides appropriate resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to all.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some developers working on the project and a community of voluntary coders.
Starting this week, technological developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee has stated that his team and he is not yet in discussion with " Facebook and Google" in order to know whether or not to make a complete change where all their business models are completely tangled in an instant.
“We don’t ask for permission.”
In an article published Saturday on Medium, Berners-Lee writes that the "mission [of Inrupt] is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem in order to protect the integrity and quality of the new web built on Solid".
In 1994, at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating the World Wide Web Consortium.
In the last few months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on the neutrality of the network.
